gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] =E2=80=93 the premier destina=
tion for discoverability-driven securities investing. As we start off the N=
ew Year, make a good decision and learn more about Alto.
(Of course, IRA rules and regulations apply, and you should seek advice fro=
m a tax professional when making investments. Alternative asset investments=
 are inherently risky and are intended for sophisticated investors.)
(1) Biden to Offer $1.5 Billion Loan to Restart Michigan Nuclear Power Plan=
t [ https://substack.com/redirect/d6b2c12c-0345-42b0-a382-7524e206918e?j=3D=
eyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Ari Natter for Bloomberg
The Biden administration is poised to lend $1.5 billion for what what would=
 be the first restart of a shuttered US nuclear reactor, the latest sign of=
 strengthening federal government support for the atomic industry.
Did Age of Miracles do it again or did Age of Miracles do it again? Uncle J=
oe must=E2=80=99ve really enjoyed Season 1, because this is about the most =
pro-nuclear thing a president has done since the 1970s!
The Biden administration plans to lend $1.5 billion to restart Holtec=E2=80=
=99s Palisades nuclear plant in Michigan, which originally closed for finan=
cial reasons. One power plant isn=E2=80=99t going to really move the needle=
 on achieving the Biden Admin=E2=80=99s climate goals, but it is a strong s=
ignal that the administration is supporting the nuclear industry. Like any =
deal like this there=E2=80=99s a bunch of local, state, and federal politic=
king going on behind the scenes =E2=80=94 how many jobs will this produce, =
will this get bipartisan support, etc., etc., =E2=80=94 but overall, this i=
nitiative reflects Biden=E2=80=99s broader strategy of maintaining nuclear =
energy's role in the U.S. energy mix.
(2) Decarbonization: Stocks and flows, abundance and scarcity, net zero [ h=
ttps://substack.com/redirect/3b849990-3060-4c29-8967-ecd0ec696d06?j=3DeyJ1I=
joiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
From Nat Bullard
Speaking of clean energy, Nat Bullard just published his annual 200-slide p=
resentation on Decarbonization. The impressive deck covers =E2=80=9Cthe sta=
te of decarbonization told with climate, capital markets, technology, and s=
ector data.=E2=80=9D You should go through all 200-slides (will take 10 min=
s), but sharing some summary points below:
Climate is getting worse: Temperatures are warming, weather is more unpredi=
ctable, glaciers are melting.
Renewables are Exploding: Solar and wind growth is insane, energy R&D is at=
 all-time highs, and markets respond to climate incentives.
Investment Opportunities: US Clean Tech investment is soaring, US manufactu=
ring is booming, there is a ton of dry powder in climate tech.
Bullard captures the point of his presentation, saying, =E2=80=9CA coherent=
 view of the future begins with the clearest possible view of the present.=
=E2=80=9D We couldn=E2=80=99t agree more.  David Deutsch=E2=80=99s Principl=
e of Optimism: =E2=80=9CAll evils are caused by insufficient knowledge.=E2=
=80=9D
(2a) US Department of Defense forms $28M partnership with Magrathea [ https=
://substack.com/redirect/88d2b168-44a6-4db1-be01-a33c3f05411f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiO=
XAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
The project will bring new primary magnesium metal supply back to the Unite=
d States for the first time in 40 years and is the US Government=E2=80=99s =
first major investment in magnesium since World War II.
Packy here. One of the challenges to decarbonization is mining and refining=
 all of raw materials we=E2=80=99ll need to make batteries, solar panels, a=
nd nuclear reactors.=20
Some people believe we=E2=80=99ll simply run out of resources. They=E2=80=
=99re wrong. As demand increases, entrepreneurs are incentivized to come up=
 with new ways to find, mine, and refine. Companies like Earth AI [ https:/=
/substack.com/redirect/6200b5a3-f2cc-4db6-b526-fea167f0892e?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXA=
wZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] are creating more eff=
ective ways to discover and test deposits. We=E2=80=99re beginning to mine =
the 3,400 kilotons of lithium in the Salton Sea [ https://substack.com/redi=
rect/608eedfa-f0bb-4ae4-b819-ed72d93cbe3b?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA=
_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], enough to support batteries for 375 mi=
llion electric vehicles. And yesterday, a startup called Magrathea announce=
d a $28 million partnership with the DoD to produce carbon neutral magnesiu=
m from seawater and brines.=20
Magrathea=E2=80=99s website says: =E2=80=9CWe=E2=80=99re developing generat=
ional upgrades to magnesium production technology that radically reduces co=
st and environmental impact.=E2=80=9D That=E2=80=99s Techno-Industrial [ ht=
tps://substack.com/redirect/34a3be40-0ee1-4538-9d79-788dd2dfc1a5?j=3DeyJ1Ij=
oiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] language, and an=
other example of my belief that the best climate companies are techno-indus=
trials in a green disguise.=20
One of my most optimistic take [ https://substack.com/redirect/170ed971-019=
3-44a0-a3e7-f1e27cd9e6c8?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKb=
qOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] is that =E2=80=9Cclimate change is a very real challenge=
 with very real negative impacts on people and the planet. But climate chan=
ge is solvable, and by solving it, we unlock the next phase of civilization=
=E2=80=99s growth.=E2=80=9D Magrathea is another piece of evidence that not=
 only are all problems solvable, by solving them, we end up in a better spo=
t than we were before.=20
(3) What to know about Elon Musk's Neuralink, which put an implant into a h=
uman brain [ https://substack.com/redirect/4cb7a789-c496-4fd1-b80f-974276a9=
3bb5?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Elon Musk says his ambitious plan to let humans wirelessly connect their br=
ains with phones and other devices has taken a new step, announcing that th=
e first human has received a brain implant from his Neuralink company.
This story is still very much developing =E2=80=94 all we have to go is a p=
ost from Elon Musk on X [ https://substack.com/redirect/0bd6803a-9c28-4581-=
80bd-0c4a22a17147?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6=
m8ExkRNpU ] =E2=80=94 but it may be the most important story of the year. A=
ccording to Musk, Neuralink has conducted its first surgical test of a brai=
n implant, the patient is recovering well, and the initial results are prom=
ising.=20
Neuralink first received FDA approval for this trial last May and said it w=
anted to enlist people with quadriplegia or ALS for the initial trial run. =
The goal of Neuralink is enable direct communication between the human brai=
n and external devices, potentially enhancing cognitive abilities and treat=
ing neurological disorders. It=E2=80=99s starting with helping to treat the=
se neurological disorders first =E2=80=94 there are fewer ethical concerns =
and the therapies have more defined solution states =E2=80=94 but it=E2=80=
=99s not hard to imagine a world in which we=E2=80=99re all walking around =
with a Neuralink implanted in our brains that hooks us up directly to an AG=
I supercomputer. The Singularity has never seemed so real.
(4) Experimental Drug Cuts Off Pain at the Source, Company Says [ https://s=
ubstack.com/redirect/63d2f101-98e9-45e8-99d5-3dc8c9b759fe?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ=
3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Gina Kolata for the New York Times
Vertex Pharmaceuticals of Boston announced Tuesday that it had developed an=
 experimental drug that relieves moderate to severe pain, blocking pain sig=
nals before they can get to the brain. It works only on peripheral nerves =
=E2=80=94 those outside the brain and the spinal cord =E2=80=94 making it u=
nlike opioids. Vertex says its new drug is expected to avoid opioids=E2=80=
=99 potential to lead to addiction.
Vertex Pharmaceuticals has developed a drug, VX-548, which relieves moderat=
e to severe pain without the addiction risks associated with opioids. VX-54=
8 targets peripheral nerves, blocking pain signals before reaching the brai=
n. Early clinical trials have shown significant pain reduction in patients =
undergoing common surgeries. VX-548 is potential breakthrough in pain treat=
ment, given its efficacy and non-additive qualities. The company plans to s=
ubmit the drug for the FDA approval process soon =E2=80=94 and given the op=
ioid crisis in the U.S., that approval can=E2=80=99t come soon enough.
(5) This AI learnt language by seeing the world through a baby=E2=80=99s ey=
es [ https://substack.com/redirect/83b6d5af-92d3-4e68-bc5f-c7bde832075e?j=
=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Elizabeth Gibney for Nature
The results suggest that AI can help us to understand how humans learn, say=
s Wai Keen Vong, co-author of the study and a researcher in AI at New York =
University. This has previously been unclear, because other language-learni=
ng models such as ChatGPT learn on billions of data points, which is not co=
mparable to the real-world experiences of an infant, says Vong. =E2=80=9CWe=
 don=E2=80=99t get given the internet when we=E2=80=99re born.=E2=80=9D
Call it Googoogag.ai cause this AI model was trained by a baby. The model, =
which was trained on a baby's headcam recordings, learned to recognize word=
s by associating them with images. The findings challenge traditional belie=
fs about innate language knowledge. The study,  which includes only 61 hour=
s of footage, showed that the AI could match words like =E2=80=9Ccrib=E2=80=
=9D and =E2=80=9Cball=E2=80=9D to images with surprising accuracy, suggesti=
ng that language learning might largely be about forming sensory associatio=
ns. Importantly, this finding contradicts theories proposed by linguists li=
ke Noam Chomsky, who argue that language acquisition requires specialized m=
echanisms beyond general learning processes.
As the old saying goes, you can=E2=80=99t teach and old dog new tricks but =
you can teach an AI by strapping a headcam to a baby.
=E2=80=A6And that=E2=80=99s all for this week.=20
If you have some time this weekend, check out Alto [ https://substack.com/r=
edirect/46e84246-c959-4c95-972e-de2e580a8137?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7=
GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].
We=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox on Tuesday.
Thanks for reading,
Dan + Packy

